# <u>PWM circuit</u>

So we need 12 pulse width modulation signal for these subcircuit:

|||
<colgroup><col /><col /></colgroup>|---|---|
|Module name|#|
|Motor #1|1|
|Motor #2|2|
|Motor #3|3|
|Motor #4|4|
|Motor #5|5|
|Motor #6|6|
|Motor #7|7|
|Motor #8|8|
|Gripper|9|
|LED|10|
|Torpedos|11|
|Expension on switch|12|

We selected the PCA9685PW for it's great number of pwm (16). It is also a well documented, easy understanding chip and has good review. There is no calcul to do here. The only important thing here is the I2C address. It is important to give an address only use by the chip itself. We can decide the address with the 6 address input. (wheter an high or low logic state, here we all connect it to gnd.) Finally, we put some decoupling capacitor close as possible to the chip on the supply. We also put an pull-up resistor on the active low enable input pin since we have an open-drain signal frome the Xavier.

Be careful!!!


You must confirm with the google doc that there's not other I2C chip using the same address.

# <u>ADC circuit</u>

In this analog to digital converter, we found the ad7997. This I2C ADC is a 10/12 bits with fast conversion and 8 analog single ended input. For the address, we have the AS pin. We also have the model to consider. Here is the table with the info:

[![](attachments/46170199/46170206.png)](https://www.analog.com/media/en/technical-documentation/data-sheets/AD7997_7998.pdf)

Since we have the AD7997-1, we put the AS on float for the first ADC and on the ground for the second one.

Be careful!!!


You must confirm with the google doc that there's not other I2C chip using the same address.

We also need decoupling on the supply with 2 capacitors to filter the power. For the voltage reference we put a 1 and 0.1uF capacitor because this is mentionned in the datasheet. We finally put a pull-up resistoron the alert/busy output since it is an open-drain signal.

# <u>HMI circuit</u>

This circuit is a basic one. It simply transfer some 3V3 signal into 5V to facilitate the communication between screen and MCU. We chose the 74LVC1T45GW.

## **Circuit**

![](attachments/46170199/46170219.png)

# <u>LED circuit</u>

these LED circuit is simple and basic. Always put a resistance in serie with the LED because the LED has a very low internal resistance and we don't want to break it. The first on the left is to show when the 3V3 is enabled. the second and the third one are for sharing visual information of the state of the submarine. We are using N-type MOSFET to reduce the drain current that could be done by the LED and resistor on the MCU. Instead, we're saving the MCU from this, and we also put 100k ohms res from the gate to the ground to discharge the gate immediately and prevent it to the MCU. We are using simple LED, and simple MOSFET N-type.

## **Circuit**

<u>![](attachments/46170199/46170214.png)</u>

# <u>Temperature sensor circuit</u>

For this circuit we could have use a simple thermistor linked to an ADC. Instead, we decide to monitor the temperature with the AT30TS750A-XM8M-T. This integrated circuit communicate in I2C. We still have 3 AS pin to change the address. We need a pull-up for the active low ALERT pin.

Still putting decoupling capacitor on the supply.

Be careful!!!


You must confirm with the google doc that there's not other I2C chip using the same address.
